# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-memorydb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-memorydb/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:aws-memorydb/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Consistency models are used in distributed systems like distributed shared memory systems or distributed data stores (such as filesystems, databases, optimistic replication systems or web caching).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Consistency is different from coherence, which occurs in systems that are cached or cache-less, and is consistency of data with respect to all processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Coherence deals with maintaining a global order in which writes to a single location or single variable are seen by all processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Consistency deals with the ordering of operations to multiple locations with respect to all processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The consistency model determines whether client B will definitely see the write performed by client A, will definitely not, or cannot depend on seeing the write.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Consistency models define rules for the apparent order and visibility of updates, and are on a continuum with tradeoffs.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are two methods to define and categorize consistency models; issue and view.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Issue method describes the restrictions that define how a process can issue operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] For example, a consistency model can define that a process is not allowed to issue an operation until all previously issued operations are completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Different consistency models enforce different conditions.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] One consistency model can be considered stronger than another if it requires all conditions of that model and more.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In other words, a model with fewer constraints is considered a weaker consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These models define how the hardware needs to be laid out and at a high-level, how the programmer must code.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The chosen model also affects how the compiler can re-order instructions.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Generally, if control dependencies between instructions and if writes to same location are ordered, then the compiler can reorder as required.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, with the models described below, some may allow writes before loads to be reordered while some may not.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Strict consistency is the strongest consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Under this model, a write to a variable by any processor needs to be seen instantaneously by all processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The strict model diagram and non-strict model diagrams describe the time constraint – instantaneous.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It can be better understood as though a global clock is present in which every write should be reflected in all processor caches by the end of that clock period.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The next operation must happen only in the next clock period.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the following diagram, P means "process" and the global clock's value is represented in the Sequence column.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In this model, the programmer's expected result will be received every time.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Its practical relevance is restricted to a thought experiment and formalism, because instantaneous message exchange is impossible.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It doesn't help in answering the question of conflict resolution in concurrent writes to the same data item, because it assumes concurrent writes to be impossible.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The sequential consistency model was proposed by Lamport (1979).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It is a weaker memory model than strict consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A write to a variable does not have to be seen instantaneously, however, writes to variables by different processors have to be seen in the same order by all processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In sequential consistency, there is no notion of time or most recent write operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are some operations interleaving that is the same for all processes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A process can see the write operations of all processes but it can just see its own read operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Program order within each processor and sequential ordering of operations between processors should be maintained.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In order to preserve sequential order of execution between processors, all operations must appear to execute instantaneously or atomically with respect to every other processor.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These operations need only "appear" to be completed because it is physically impossible to send information instantaneously.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] For instance, in a system utilizing a single globally shared bus, once a bus line is posted with information, it is guaranteed that all processors will see the information at the same instant.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Thus, passing the information to the bus line completes the execution with respect to all processors and has appeared to have been executed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Cache-less architectures or cached architectures with interconnect networks that are not instantaneous can contain a slow path between processors and memories.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These slow paths can result in sequential inconsistency, because some memories receive the broadcast data faster than others.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Sequential consistency can produce non-deterministic results.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This is because the sequence of sequential operations between processors can be different during different runs of the program.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] All memory operations need to happen in the program order.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Linearizability (also known as atomic consistency or atomic memory) can be defined as sequential consistency with a real-time constraint, by considering a begin time and end time for each operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] An execution is linearizable if each operation taking place in linearizable order by placing a point between its begin time and its end time and guarantees sequential consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Verifying sequential consistency through model checking is undecidable in general, even for finite-state cache coherence protocols.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Causal consistency defined by Hutto and Ahamad, 1990, is a weakening of the sequential consistency model by categorizing events into those causally related and those that are not.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It defines that only write operations that are causally related, need to be seen in the same order by all processes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] For example, if an event b takes effect from an earlier event a, the causal consistency guarantees that all processes see event b after event a.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This model relaxes sequential consistency on concurrent writes by a processor and on writes that are not causally related.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Two writes can become causally related if one write to a variable is dependent on a previous write to any variable if the processor doing the second write has just read the first write.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The two writes could have been done by the same processor or by different processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] As in sequential consistency, reads do not need to reflect changes instantaneously, however, they need to reflect all changes to a variable sequentially.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] W(x)2 happens after W(x)1 due to the read made by P2 to x before W(x)2, hence this example is *causally consistent* under Hutto and Ahamad's definition (although not under Tanenbaum et al.'s, because W(x)2 and W(x)3 are not seen in the same order for all processes).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However R(x)2 and R(x)3 happen in a different order on P3 and P4, hence this example is *sequentially inconsistent*.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In order for consistency in data to be maintained and to attain scalable processor systems where every processor has its own memory, the processor consistency model was derived.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] All processors need to be consistent in the order in which they see writes done by one processor and in the way they see writes by different processors to the same location (coherence is maintained).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, they do not need to be consistent when the writes are by different processors to different locations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Every write operation can be divided into several sub-writes to all memories.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A read from one such memory can happen before the write to this memory completes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Thus, a processor under PC can execute a younger load when an older store needs to be stalled.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Read before write, read after read and write before write ordering is still preserved in this model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The processor consistency model is similar to the PRAM consistency model with a stronger condition that defines all writes to the same memory location must be seen in the same sequential order by all other processes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Processor consistency is weaker than sequential consistency but stronger than the PRAM consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The Stanford DASH multiprocessor system implements a variation of processor consistency which is incomparable (neither weaker nor stronger) to Goodman's definitions.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] All processors need to be consistent in the order in which they see writes by one processor and in the way they see writes by different processors to the same location.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Pipelined RAM consistency (PRAM consistency) was presented by Lipton and Sandberg in 1988 as one of the first described consistency models.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Due to its informal definition, there are in fact at least two subtly different implementations, one by Ahamad et al. and one by Mosberger.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In PRAM consistency, all processes view the operations of a single process in the same order that they were issued by that process, while operations issued by different processes can be viewed in different order from different processes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] PRAM consistency is weaker than processor consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] PRAM relaxes the need to maintain coherence to a location across all its processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Here, reads to any variable can be executed before writes in a processor.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Cache consistency requires that all write operations to the same memory location are performed in some sequential order.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Cache consistency is weaker than processor consistency and incomparable with PRAM consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In slow consistency, if a process reads a value previously written to a memory location, it cannot subsequently read any earlier value from that location.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Writes performed by a process are immediately visible to that process.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Slow consistency is a weaker model than PRAM and cache consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Hutto, Phillip W., and Mustaque Ahamad (1990) illustrate that by appropriate programming, slow memory (consistency) can be expressive and efficient.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] They mention that slow memory has two valuable properties; locality and supporting reduction from atomic memory.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] They propose two algorithms to present the expressiveness of slow memory.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These 4 consistency models were proposed in a 1994 paper.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] They focus on guarantees in the situation where only a single user or application is making data modifications.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] If a process reads the value of a data item x, any successive read operation on x by that process will always return that same value or a more recent value.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A write operation by a process on a data item X is completed before any successive write operation on X by the same process.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A value written by a process on a data item X will always be available to a successive read operation performed by the same process on data item X.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A write operation by a process on a data item x following a previous read operation on x by the same process is guaranteed to take place on the same or a more recent value of x that was read.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The following models require specific synchronization by programmers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Weak ordering classifies memory operations into two categories: *data operations* and *synchronization operations*.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] To enforce program order, a programmer needs to find at least one synchronisation operation in a program.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Synchronization operations signal the processor to make sure it has completed and seen all previous operations done by all processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Program order and atomicity is maintained only on synchronisation operations and not on all reads and writes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This was derived from the understanding that certain memory operations – such as those conducted in a critical section - need not be seen by all processors until after all operations in the critical section are completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It assumes reordering memory operations to data regions between synchronisation operations does not affect the outcome of the program.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This exploits the fact that programs written to be executed on a multi-processor system contain the required synchronization to make sure that data races do not occur and SC outcomes are produced always.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Once these requirements are met, all other "data" operations can be reordered.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The way this works is that a counter tracks the number of data operations and until this counter becomes zero, the synchronisation operation isn't issued.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Furthermore, no more data operations are issued unless all the previous synchronisations are completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Memory operations in between two synchronisation variables can be overlapped and reordered without affecting the correctness of the program.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This model ensures that write atomicity is always maintained, therefore no additional safety net is required for weak ordering.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In order to maintain weak ordering, write operations prior to a synchronization operation must be globally performed before the synchronization operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Operations present after a synchronization operation should also be performed only after the synchronization operation completes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Therefore, accesses to synchronization variables is sequentially consistent and any read or write should be performed only after previous synchronization operations have completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There is high reliance on explicit synchronization in the program.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] For weak ordering models, the programmer must use atomic locking instructions such as test-and-set, fetch-and-op, store conditional, load linked or must label synchronization variables or use fences.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The release consistency model relaxes the weak consistency model by distinguishing the entrance synchronization operation from the exit synchronization operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Under weak ordering, when a synchronization operation is to be seen, all operations in all processors need to be visible before the synchronization operation is done and the processor proceeds.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, under the release consistency model, during the entry to a critical section, termed as "acquire", all operations with respect to the local memory variables need to be completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] During the exit, termed as "release", all changes made by the local processor should be propagated to all other processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The acquire operation is a load/read that is performed to access the critical section.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A release operation is a store/write performed to allow other processors to use the shared variables.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Among synchronization variables, sequential consistency or processor consistency can be maintained.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Using SC, all competing synchronization variables should be processed in order.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, with PC, a pair of competing variables need to only follow this order.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Younger acquires can be allowed to happen before older releases.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are two types of release consistency, release consistency with sequential consistency (RCsc) and release consistency with processor consistency (RCpc).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The latter type denotes which type of consistency is applied to those operations nominated below as special.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are special (cf. ordinary) memory operations, themselves consisting of two classes of operations: *sync* or *nsync* operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The latter are operations not used for synchronisation; the former are, and consist of *acquire* and *release* operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] An acquire is effectively a read memory operation used to obtain access to a certain set of shared locations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Release, on the other hand, is a write operation that is performed for granting permission to access the shared locations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Note: the above notation A → B, implies that if the operation A precedes B in the program order, then program order is enforced.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This is a variant of the release consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It also requires the use of *acquire* and *release* instructions to explicitly state an entry or exit to a critical section.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, under entry consistency, every shared variable is assigned a synchronization variable specific to it.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This way, only when the acquire is to variable x, all operations related to x need to be completed with respect to that processor.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This allows concurrent operations of different critical sections of different shared variables to occur.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Concurrency cannot be seen for critical operations on the same shared variable.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Such a consistency model will be useful when different matrix elements can be processed at the same time.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In local consistency, each process performs its own operations in the order defined by its program.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There is no constraint on the ordering in which the write operations of other processes appear to be performed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Local consistency is the weakest consistency model in shared memory systems.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In general consistency, all the copies of a memory location are eventually identical after all processes' writes are completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] An eventual consistency is a weak consistency model in a system with the lack of simultaneous updates.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It defines that if no update takes a very long time, all replicas eventually become consistent.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Some different consistency models can be defined by relaxing one or more requirements in sequential consistency called relaxed consistency models.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These consistency models do not provide memory consistency at the hardware level.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In fact, the programmers are responsible for implementing the memory consistency by applying synchronization techniques.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The above models are classified based on four criteria and are detailed further.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] One way to categorize the relaxed consistency is to define which sequential consistency requirements are relaxed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] We can have less strict models by relaxing either program order or write atomicity requirements defined by Adve and Gharachorloo, 1996.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Program order guarantees that each process issues a memory request ordered by its program and write atomicity defines that memory requests are serviced based on the order of a single FIFO queue.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In relaxing program order, any or all the ordering of operation pairs, write-after-write, read-after-write, or read/write-after-read, can be relaxed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the relaxed write atomicity model, a process can view its own writes before any other processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A synchronizing model can be defined by dividing the memory accesses into two groups and assigning different consistency restrictions to each group considering that one group can have a weak consistency model while the other one needs a more restrictive consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In contrast, a non-synchronizing model assigns the same consistency model to the memory access types.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Issue method provides sequential consistency simulation by defining the restrictions for processes to issue memory operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Whereas, view method describes the visibility restrictions on the events order for processes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Some consistency models are more restrictive than others.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In other words, strict consistency models enforce more constraints as consistency requirements.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The strength of a model can be defined by the program order or atomicity relaxations and the strength of models can also be compared.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Some models are directly related if they apply the same relaxations or more.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] On the other hand, the models that relax different requirements are not directly related.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Sequential consistency has two requirements, program order and write atomicity.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Different relaxed consistency models can be obtained by relaxing these requirements.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This is done so that, along with relaxed constraints, the performance increases, but the programmer is responsible for implementing the memory consistency by applying synchronisation techniques and must have a good understanding of the hardware.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] An approach to improving the performance at the hardware level is by relaxing the PO of a write followed by a read which effectively hides the latency of write operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The optimisation this type of relaxation relies on is that it allows the subsequent reads to be in a relaxed order with respect to the previous writes from the processor.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Because of this relaxation some programs like XXX may fail to give SC results because of this relaxation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Whereas, programs like YYY are still expected to give consistent results because of the enforcement of the remaining program order constraints.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The IBM 370 model is the strictest model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A read can be complete before an earlier write to a different address, but it is prohibited from returning the value of the write unless all the processors have seen the write.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The SPARC V8 total store ordering model (TSO) model partially relaxes the IBM 370 Model, it allows a read to return the value of its own processor's write with respect to other writes to the same location i.e. it returns the value of its own write before others see it.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Similar to the previous model, this cannot return the value of write unless all the processors have seen the write.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The processor consistency model (PC) is the most relaxed of the three models and relaxes both the constraints such that a read can complete before an earlier write even before it is made visible to other processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In Example A, the result is possible only in IBM 370 because read(A) is not issued until the write(A) in that processor is completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] On the other hand, this result is possible in TSO and PC because they allow the reads of the flags before the writes of the flags in a single processor.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In Example B the result is possible only with PC as it allows P2 to return the value of a write even before it is visible to P3.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This won't be possible in the other two models.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] To ensure sequential consistency in the above models, safety nets or fences are used to manually enforce the constraint.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The IBM370 model has some specialised *serialisation instructions* which are manually placed between operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These instructions can consist of memory instructions or non-memory instructions such as branches.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] On the other hand, the TSO and PC models do not provide safety nets, but the programmers can still use read-modify-write operations to make it appear like the program order is still maintained between a write and a following read.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In case of TSO, PO appears to be maintained if the R or W which is already a part of a R-modify-W is replaced by a R-modify-W, this requires the W in the R-modify-W is a ‘dummy’ that returns the read value.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Similarly for PC, PO seems to be maintained if the read is replaced by a write or is already a part of R-modify-W.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, compiler optimisations cannot be done after exercising this relaxation alone.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Compiler optimisations require the full flexibility of reordering any two operations in the PO, so the ability to reorder a write with respect to a read is not sufficiently helpful in this case.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Some models relax the program order even further by relaxing even the ordering constraints between writes to different locations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The SPARC V8 partial store ordering model (PSO) is the only example of such a model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The ability to pipeline and overlap writes to different locations from the same processor is the key hardware optimisation enabled by PSO.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] PSO is similar to TSO in terms of atomicity requirements, in that it allows a processor to read the value of its own write and prevents other processors from reading another processor's write before the write is visible to all other processors.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Program order between two writes is maintained by PSO using an explicit STBAR instruction.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The STBAR is inserted in a write buffer in implementations with FIFO write buffers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A counter is used to determine when all the writes before the STBAR instruction have been completed, which triggers a write to the memory system to increment the counter.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A write acknowledgement decrements the counter, and when the counter becomes 0, it signifies that all the previous writes are completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the examples A and B, PSO allows both these non-sequentially consistent results.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The safety net that PSO provides is similar to TSO's, it imposes program order from a write to a read and enforces write atomicity.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Similar to the previous models, the relaxations allowed by PSO are not sufficiently flexible to be useful for compiler optimisation, which requires a much more flexible optimisation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In some models, all operations to different locations are relaxed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A read or write may be reordered with respect to a different read or write in a different location.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The *weak ordering* may be classified under this category and two types of release consistency models (RCsc and RCpc) also come under this model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Three commercial architectures are also proposed under this category of relaxation: the Digital Alpha, SPARC V9 relaxed memory order (RMO), and IBM PowerPC models.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These three commercial architectures exhibit explicit fence instructions as their safety nets.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The Alpha model provides two types of fence instructions, *memory barrier* (MB) and *write memory barrier* (WMB).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The MB operation can be used to maintain program order of any memory operation before the MB with a memory operation after the barrier.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Similarly, the WMB maintains program order only among writes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The SPARC V9 RMO model provides a MEMBAR instruction which can be customised to order previous reads and writes with respect to future read and write operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There is no need for using read-modify-writes to achieve this order because the MEMBAR instruction can be used to order a write with respect to a succeeding read.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The PowerPC model uses a single fence instruction called the SYNC instruction.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It is similar to the MB instruction, but with a little exception that reads can occur out of program order even if a SYNC is placed between two reads to the same location.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This model also differs from Alpha and RMO in terms of atomicity.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It allows a write to be seen earlier than a read's completion.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A combination of read modify write operations may be required to make an illusion of write atomicity.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] RMO and PowerPC allow reordering of reads to the same location.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] These models violate sequential order in examples A and B.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] An additional relaxation allowed in these models is that memory operations following a read operation can be overlapped and reordered with respect to the read.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Alpha and RMO allow a read to return the value of another processor's early write.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] From a programmer's perspective these models must maintain the illusion of write atomicity even though they allow the processor to read its own write early.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Transactional memory model is the combination of cache coherency and memory consistency models as a communication model for shared memory systems supported by software or hardware; a transactional memory model provides both memory consistency and cache coherency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A transaction is a sequence of operations executed by a process that transforms data from one consistent state to another.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A transaction either commits when there is no conflict or aborts.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In commits, all changes are visible to all other processes when a transaction is completed, while aborts discard all changes.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Compared to relaxed consistency models, a transactional model is easier to use and can provide higher performance than a sequential consistency model.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Several other consistency models have been conceived to express restrictions with respect to ordering or visibility of operations, or to deal with specific fault assumptions.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 defines two main reasons for replicating; reliability and performance.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Reliability can be achieved in a replicated file system by switching to another replica in the case of the current replica failure.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The replication also protects data from being corrupted by providing multiple copies of data on different replicas.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It also improves the performance by dividing the work.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] While replication can improve performance and reliability, it can cause consistency problems between multiple copies of data.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The multiple copies are consistent if a read operation returns the same value from all copies and a write operation as a single atomic operation (transaction) updates all copies before any other operation takes place.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Tanenbaum, Andrew, & Maarten Van Steen, 2007 refer to this type of consistency as **tight consistency** provided by synchronous replication.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] However, applying global synchronizations to keep all copies consistent is costly.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] One way to decrease the cost of global synchronization and improve the performance can be weakening the consistency restrictions.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 defines the **consistency model** as a contract between the software (processes) and memory implementation (data store).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This model guarantees that if the software follows certain rules, the memory works correctly.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Since, in a system without a global clock, defining the last operation among writes is difficult, some restrictions can be applied on the values that can be returned by a read operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The goal of data-centric consistency models is to provide a consistent view on a data store where processes may carry out concurrent updates.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Some consistency models such as sequential and also causal consistency models deal with the order of operations on shared replicated data in order to provide consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In these models, all replicas must agree on a consistent global ordering of updates.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In grouping operation, accesses to the synchronization variables are sequentially consistent.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A process is allowed to access a synchronization variable that all previous writes have been completed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In other words, accesses to synchronization variables are not permitted until all operations on the synchronization variables are completely performed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In distributed systems, maintaining sequential consistency in order to control the concurrent operations is essential.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In some special data stores without simultaneous updates, client-centric consistency models can deal with inconsistencies in a less costly way.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The implementation of a consistency model is defined by a consistency protocol.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 illustrates some consistency protocols for data-centric models.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Continuous consistency introduced by Yu and Vahdat (2000).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In this model, the consistency semantics of an application is described by using conits in the application.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Since the consistency requirements can differ based on application semantics, Yu and Vahdat (2000) believe that a predefined uniform consistency model may not be an appropriate approach.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The application should specify the consistency requirements that satisfy the application semantics.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In this model, an application specifies each consistency requirement as a conit (abbreviation of consistency units).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A conit can be a physical or logical consistency and is used to measure the consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Tanenbaum et al., 2007 describes the notion of a conit by giving an example.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are three inconsistencies that can be tolerated by applications.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Numerical deviation bounds the difference between the conit value and the relative value of the last update.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A weight can be assigned to the writes which defines the importance of the writes in a specific application.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The total weights of unseen writes for a conit can be defined as a numerical deviation in an application.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are two different types of numerical deviation; absolute and relative numerical deviation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Ordering deviation is the discrepancy between the local order of writes in a replica and their relative ordering in the eventual final image.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Staleness deviation defines the validity of the oldest write by bounding the difference between the current time and the time of the oldest write on a conit not seen locally.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Each server has a local queue of uncertain write that is required an actual order to be determined and applied on a conit.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The maximal length of uncertain writes queue is the bound of ordering deviation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] When the number of writes exceeds the limit, instead of accepting new submitted write, the server will attempt to commit uncertain writes by communicating with other servers based on the order that writes should be executed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] If all three deviation bounds are set to zero, the continuous consistency model is the strong consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Primary-based protocols can be considered as a class of consistency protocols that are simpler to implement.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] For instance, sequential ordering is a popular consistency model when consistent ordering of operations is considered.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The sequential ordering can be determined as primary-based protocol.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In these protocols, there is an associated primary for each data item in a data store to coordinate write operations on that data item.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the simplest primary-based protocol that supports replication, also known as primary-backup protocol, write operations are forwarded to a single server and read operations can be performed locally.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] gives an example of a primary-backup protocol.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The diagram of primary-backup protocol shows an example of this protocol.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] When a client requests a write, the write request is forwarded to a primary server.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The primary server sends request to backups to perform the update.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The server then receives the update acknowledgement from all backups and sends the acknowledgement of completion of writes to the client.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Any client can read the last available update locally.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The trade-off of this protocol is that a client who sends the update request might have to wait so long to get the acknowledgement in order to continue.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This problem can be solved by performing the updates locally, and then asking other backups to perform their updates.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The non-blocking primary-backup protocol does not guarantee the consistency of update on all backup servers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the primary-backup protocol, all processes will see the same order of write operations since this protocol orders all incoming writes based on a globally unique time.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Blocking protocols guarantee that processes view the result of the last write operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In primary-based local-write protocols, primary copy moves between processes willing to perform an update.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] To update a data item, a process first moves it to its location.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] As a result, in this approach, successive write operations can be performed locally while each process can read their local copy of data items.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] After the primary finishes its update, the update is forwarded to other replicas and all perform the update locally.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] This non-blocking approach can lead to an improvement.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The diagram of the local-write protocol depicts the local-write approach in primary-based protocols.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A process requests a write operation in a data item x.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The current server is considered as the new primary for a data item x.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The write operation is performed and when the request is finished, the primary sends an update request to other backup servers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Each backup sends an acknowledgment to the primary after finishing the update operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In replicated-write protocols, unlike the primary-based protocol, all updates are carried out to all replicas.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In active replication, there is a process associated with each replica to perform the write operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In other words, updates are sent to each replica in the form of an operation in order to be executed.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] All updates need to be performed in the same order in all replicas.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] As a result, a totally-ordered multicast mechanism is required.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There is a scalability issue in implementing such a multicasting mechanism in large distributed systems.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There is another approach in which each operation is sent to a central coordinator (sequencer).
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The coordinator first assigns a sequence number to each operation and then forwards the operation to all replicas.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Second approach cannot also solve the scalability problem.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Voting can be another approach in replicated-write protocols.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In this approach, a client requests and receives permission from multiple servers in order to read and write a replicated data.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] As an example, suppose in a distributed file system, a file is replicated on N servers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] To update a file, a client must send a request to at least N/2 + 1 in order to make their agreement to perform an update.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] After the agreement, changes are applied on the file and a new version number is assigned to the updated file.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Similarly, for reading replicated file, a client sends a request to N/2 + 1 servers in order to receive the associated version number from those servers.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Read operation is completed if all received version numbers are the most recent version.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In a replicated file system, a cache-coherence protocol provides the cache consistency while caches are generally controlled by clients.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In many approaches, cache consistency is provided by the underlying hardware.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Some other approaches in middleware-based distributed systems apply software-based solutions to provide the cache consistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Cache consistency models can differ in their coherence detection strategies that define when inconsistencies occur.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] There are two approaches to detect the inconsistency; static and dynamic solutions.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the static solution, a compiler determines which variables can cause the cache inconsistency.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] So, the compiler enforces an instruction in order to avoid the inconsistency problem.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the dynamic solution, the server checks for inconsistencies at run time to control the consistency of the cached data that has changed after it was cached.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] The coherence enforcement strategy is another cache-coherence protocol.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] It defines *how* to provide the consistency in caches by using the copies located on the server.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] One way to keep the data consistent is to never cache the shared data.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] A server can keep the data and apply some consistency protocol such as primary-based protocols to ensure the consistency of shared data.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In this solution, only private data can be cached by clients.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the case that shared data is cached, there are two approaches in order to enforce the cache coherence.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the first approach, when a shared data is updated, the server forwards invalidation to all caches.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] In the second approach, an update is propagated.
[src:aws-memorydb/consistency-model] Most caching systems apply these two approaches or dynamically choose between them.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:aws-memorydb/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:aws-memorydb/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:aws-memorydb/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
